data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 9, the Cosmos DB provider began **blocking synchronous LINQ operations by default**, throwing `InvalidOperationException`. You could opt back in via:

```csharp
options.UseCosmos(..., cosmosOptions =>
    cosmosOptions.AllowSynchronousIO());
```

**In EF Core 11 (targeting .NET 11), that opt-in is removed entirely.** The Cosmos provider no longer supports sync-over-async at all. Every synchronous call — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — will throw `InvalidOperationException` with no workaround.

## How to Fix

Convert all repository methods to their async equivalents:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return `Task<T>` / `Task` instead of `T` / `void`
- Use `ToListAsync()`, `FirstAsync()`, `CountAsync()`, `SaveChangesAsync()`
- Mark methods `async` and `await` each call
- Rename methods with `Async` suffix (convention)

This will ripple up through your call chain — callers must also become async (`async`/`await` all the way up to the controller actions). If your controllers aren't already async, they'll need the same treatment.
